    "title": {
        "rendered": "Reworking Theme Files &amp; Organization"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-11264\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-01.jpg?resize=1024%2C384&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"basics-theme-files-organization-01\" width=\"1024\" height=\"384\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-01.jpg?w=1024&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-01.jpg?resize=300%2C112&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px\" /></p>\n<h2>Theme folder and file structure</h2>\n<p>While WordPress themes technically only require two files (<code>index.php</code> and <code>style.css</code>), they usually are made up of many files and can become quickly disorganized.</p>\n<p>In the last section, <a title=\"Template Files\" href=\"#\">Template Files</a>, you set up your <code>header.php, footer.php, page.php, home.php, and single.php</code> files.</p>\n<p>Let&#8217;s look at \u00a0the\u00a0<a href=\"https://wordpress.org/themes/twentytwelve\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Twenty Twelve theme</a>\u00a0default themes as\u00a0one example of good file structure and organization. \u00a0While this may be a bit overwhelming at first, let&#8217;s break it down. \u00a0Can you find the templates you just built?</p>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-11265\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-02.png?resize=629%2C1500&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"basics-theme-files-organization-02\" width=\"629\" height=\"1500\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-02.png?w=629&amp;ssl=1 629w, https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-02.png?resize=429%2C1024&amp;ssl=1 429w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 629px) 100vw, 629px\" /></p>\n<p>While there are still a lot of files, their names help provide a context\u00a0of what they are. \u00a0Basically each file handles a feature of WordPress. \u00a0I.e. <code>comments.php</code> deals with how the theme will handle comments; <code>image.php</code> instructs the theme how to handle images, etc. \u00a0Don&#8217;t worry about adding these files unless\u00a0you need them.</p>\n<p>You can see that the main theme template files are in the theme&#8217;s root directory, while JavaScript, languages, CSS, and page template files are placed within their own folders.</p>\n<p>At this time there are <strong>no required folders within a WordPress theme</strong>. However, WordPress does recognize the following folders by default:</p>\n<h3>Page templates folder</h3>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-11267\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-03.png?resize=400%2C124&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"basics-theme-files-organization-03\" width=\"400\" height=\"124\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-03.png?w=400&amp;ssl=1 400w, https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-03.png?resize=300%2C93&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px\" /></p>\n<p>The <a title=\"Custom Page Templates\" href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/themes/basics/page-templates/\">custom page templates</a>, named <em>page-templates</em> (since: 3.4.0) allows for better organization of template files. Custom page template files placed in this folder are automatically recognized by WordPress.</p>\n<h3>Language folder</h3>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-11268\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-04.png?resize=400%2C85&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"basics-theme-files-organization-04\" width=\"400\" height=\"85\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-04.png?w=400&amp;ssl=1 400w, https://i0.wp.com/developer.wordpress.org/files/2014/08/basics-theme-files-organization-04.png?resize=300%2C63&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px\" /></p>\n<p>If you wish to <a title=\"Internationalization\" href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/themes/functionality/internationalization/\">internationalize your theme</a> so it&#8217;s usable in other languages, you can create a <em>languages</em> folder to contain translations.</p>\n",
